{
  "text": "Centrosome, the major microtubule-organizing center (MTOC) in vertebrate cells, provides a major site for microtubule (MT) nucleation and plays key roles in bipolar spindle assembly during mitosis [CITATION_1] . A typical centrosome consists of a pair of centrioles surrounded by the pericentriolar matrix (PCM) [CITATION_2] . Many proteins, including γ-tubulin (GCP1), γ-tubulin complex proteins (GCPs) and a large number of other centrosome-associated proteins, localize to PCM and are involved in the formation of mitotic spindles. Together with other GCPs, γ-tubulin forms two distinctly sized complexes: the γ-tubulin small complex (γ-TuSC) and the γ-tubulin ring complex (γ-TuRC). The γ-TuSC is a heterotetramer consisting of two copies of γ-tubulin and one copy each of GCP2 and GCP3/Tubgcp3. Seven γ-TuSCs with GCP4, GCP5, GCP6 and other accessory proteins assemble into the γ-TuRC, which facilitates MT nucleation by capping the minus ends of MTs and protecting them from depolymerization [CITATION_3] . Centrosomes have critical roles in brain development, and mutations in genes encoding for centrosome-associated proteins have been shown to be genetically linked to neurodevelopmental disorders [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
